# Contributor workflow

The rules below highlight the requirements that are most often missed when contributing to the
Zesu documentation site.

## Sidebar updates

The sidebar is **manually defined** in `sidebars.js`. New pages do not appear in the navigation
until they are added there.

When adding, moving, or removing a page:

1. Edit `sidebars.js` to add the page ID under the correct category, in the intended position.
2. Verify the order matches the reader's expected progression (for example, onboarding pages
   before advanced topics).
3. Preview locally with `npm start` to confirm the page renders in the right place.

The page ID is the path under `docs/` without the file extension (for example,
`how-to/configure` for `docs/how-to/configure.md`).

## Redirects

Every deleted, renamed, or moved page must have a redirect added in `vercel.json`. Docusaurus is
configured with `onBrokenLinks: 'throw'` and `onBrokenMarkdownLinks: 'throw'`, so broken
internal links will fail the build.

## Factual accuracy

Do not state as fact any CLI option, configuration setting, API behavior, parameter, or return
value that you have not verified against the Zesu codebase or published reference. If you are
uncertain, add a review comment or admonition noting the uncertainty. This rule applies to both
human and AI-assisted contributions.

## Images

Place images in `docs/assets/images/` (create the directory if it does not exist). Reference
them with relative paths from the documentation page.

## Update rule files for structural changes

When a change affects the structure, naming, or conventions of the documentation, update the
corresponding `.cursor/rules/` file in the same PR. Examples of changes that require a rule update:

- Renaming the product or changing its branding (update `product-zesu.mdc` and `terminology.mdc`).
- Adding, removing, or renaming top-level content folders (update `product-zesu.mdc` and
  `content-types.mdc` if a new folder pattern is introduced).
- Changing the parameter documentation format in a reference section (update `product-zesu.mdc`
  and `content-types.mdc`).
- Moving image storage to a different directory (update `contributor-workflow.mdc` and
  `product-zesu.mdc`).
- Switching the sidebar from manual to autogenerated (update `contributor-workflow.mdc`,
  `product-zesu.mdc`, and `AGENTS.md`).

Keeping rule files current prevents stale guidance from producing incorrect contributions.

## CI linting

Pull requests are checked by the
[Consensys docs-lint-all](https://github.com/Consensys/github-actions) action that enforces
Microsoft style, Consensys terminology, and spelling. Fix any linter warnings before requesting
review. If a warning is a false positive, add the term to the Vale vocabulary file rather than
rewriting valid technical language.

Additional CI checks include link checking, markdown linting, and the Docusaurus build (which
fails on broken internal links).

## Pull requests

- Summarize what changed and why in the PR description. Do not just list files.
- Link the related issue using `fixes #<number>` when applicable.
- Preview locally with `npm start` before requesting review.
